<TITLE> AL advisory council meets Tuesday </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 25 (bdnews24.com)  Members of the ruling Awami League Advisory Council will meet on Tuesday, almost a year after the formation of the new committee. The meeting will be held in the evening at Gano Bahban, with the Prime Minister and party chief Sheikh Hasina in the chair. At the meeting will be leaders who have long been working as policy makers in the party but were dropped from the Central Working Committee, during the party council, in July 2009. Among those dropped were Amir Hossain Amu, Abdur Razzak, Tofail Ahmed, Suranjit Sengupta and Abdul Jalil. According to the AL constitution, the advisory council has no jurisdiction in policy making, and its political, social and economic cells can only offer suggestions or guidelines, inline with national and international considerations. The advisory council can have as many as 41 members, but at present there are only 20 members. Among the advisory council members are Sheikh Hasina's former political adviser, SA Malek; incumbent advisers, HT Imam, Alauddin Ahmed and Moshiur Rahman; and Finance Minister AMA Muhith; former presidium members, Amir Hossain Amu, Abdur Razzak, Tofail Ahmed, Suranjit Sengupta, and, former general secretary, Abdul Jalil; former MP, KM Safiullah; former minister MA Mannan; MPs, Dewan Farid Gazi, Rahmat Ali, and Prof MA Mannan; former vice chancellor of Dhaka University, AK Azad; former VC of Rajshahi University, Abdul Khalek; Kazi Akramuddin; SM Nurunnabi; and advocate Syed Rezaur Rahman. bdne
